Structural Changes Made to Harmony House Design

The walls of the house have been lowered resulting in a house with a lower roof. These changes were made because we realized that the taller walls would would be structurally difficult to construct onsite. Welcome back, Decatheletes!

The new semester has started off on a high note as Solar Decathlon welcomed 36 new members at the first General Body Meeting on September 1st! We’re excited to discover the potential of our new decathletes as they dive right into the nitty gritty details of the project and join committees ranging from Engineering and Energy Modeling, to Communications and Finance, to Construction and Design. This years’ new recruits come from majors across Vanderbilt’s campus, deviating from our group of engineers. We have new and fresh perspectives from economics, marketing, chemistry and human development.

E3 Innovate, a local Nashville company, works with homeowners, architects and builders to help make homes sustainable without sacrificing comfort. Consultants work to create LEED certified structures, and they have been generous enough to provide Team Tennessee with free advising. Stephan Petere-Contesse is the representative working on Harmony House and has been a huge help for our engineering team. Learn more about E3 Innovate and the awesome work they are doing in Nashville, as well as the qualifications for an LEED certified house at their website. http://www.e3innovate.com/
